'''Elizabeth Mary Edmondson'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=970781&search_type=quick&showInd=true|title=Edmondson, Elizabeth Mary|publisher=It's an Honour|accessdate=11 January 2012}}</ref> (born 1 July 1950) is an Australian Paralympic competitor and current Australian Masters competitor in swimming.  She became a [[paraplegia|paraplegic]] after contracting [[polio]] as a small child. She won several medals in the [[1964 Summer Paralympics|1964]] and [[1968 Summer Paralympics|1968]] Summer Paralympics.  She subsequently retired from swimming, only taking up the sport again in 2006 to compete in the 2008 [[FINA World Masters Championships]] in Perth.

==Early life==
[[File:Elizabeth Edmondson learning to walk.png|thumb|left|Edmondson learning to walk]]
Elizabeth Edmondson was born on 1 July 1950 in [[Perth, Western Australia]].<ref name=perth-girl>{{cite news|title=Gold Medals to Perth Girl|publisher=[[Australian Associated Press|AAP]], [[Reuters]]|work=[[The Age]]|page=13|date=11 November 1964|location=Melbourne, Victoria}}</ref> On 27 September 1951,<ref name=Stinger>{{cite web|url=http://www.westcoastswimclub.com.au/assets/stinger/2008/stinger_2008jun.pdf|accessdate=18 September 2011|title=My Story|first=Elizabeth|last=Edmondson|date=June 2008|work=The Stinger|publisher=West Coast Swim Club|format=PDF|location=Western Australia, Australia}}</ref> at the age of 15 months,<ref name=perth-girl/><ref name=Stinger/> she was diagnosed with [[Poliomyelitis|polio]].  She spent fifteen months in the hospital.  Her father made changes to the house to make it easier for her to get around, including the addition of parallel bars to help her learn to walk.  She started swimming when she was five years old,<ref name=Stinger/> at Crawley Baths in the Swan River.  The first strokes she learnt to swim were the backstroke, dog paddle and freestyle.<ref name=newsletter-6>{{cite journal|url=http://www.hconc.org.au/publications/01%20Health%20Matters/Health%20Matters%20%20Issue%2081%20Pages%201-30.pdf|accessdate=19 September 2011|page=6|journal=Your Voice on Health|publisher=The Health Consumers‘ Council WA|issue=81|date=July–September 2010|title=The Jelly Bean Walk — My Story|last=Edmondson|first=Elizabeth|format=PDF}}</ref> She learnt to swim without using her legs.<ref name=newsletter-7>{{cite journal|url=http://www.hconc.org.au/publications/01%20Health%20Matters/Health%20Matters%20%20Issue%2081%20Pages%201-30.pdf|accessdate=19 September 2011|page=7|journal=Your Voice on Health|publisher=The Health Consumers‘ Council WA|issue=81|date=July–September 2010|title=The Jelly Bean Walk — My Story|last=Edmondson|first=Elizabeth|format=PDF}}</ref> She first placed in a swimming competition during a competition in year one at school, where she finished third in a dog paddle swim.<ref name=newsletter-7/>

Her first [[orthotics|calliper]] did not allow her to bend her knee.<ref name=Stinger/> She was excited to receive her first calliper that allowed her knee to bend when she was ten years old. Edmondson had other issues with footwear as a youngster.  As her feet grew, she outgrew her custom-made footwear.  To extend the life of her shoes, the toes were cut out of them to provide more space for her own toes.<ref name=newsletter-7/>

==Competitive career==

===Beginnings===
{{Quote box
|align=right
|width=20%
|quote=Tony suggested I joined his Swimming Squad at Beatty Park, which I did. One day Tony came up to me and said "You have just broken a world record."
|source=Elizabeth Edmondson<ref name=newsletter-7/>
}}
When Edmonson was 14, her coach told her she had broken a world record while swimming at [[Beatty Park]] as a member of the Swimming Squad.<ref name=newsletter-7/> To qualify for the 1964 Summer Paralympics, she competed at the Third Australian Paraplegic Games held in Adelaide, South Australia.<ref name=paragamesad>{{cite book|title=Official programme, Third Australian Paraplegic Games, Adelaide, South Australia, September&nbsp;10–12 1964|publisher=Royal Adelaide Hospital Paraplegic Unit|author1=The Paraplegic Association of South Australia|author2= The Paraplegic Sports Club of South Australia|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/33635960?q=%22paraplegic%22&c=book}}</ref>  At the Australian Paraplegic Games in 1964, she broke a world record and a Commonwealth record.  She won a gold medal in the 50m backstroke class e event with a time of 51.8 seconds, 15.2 seconds faster than the previous Commonwealth record time that she beat.<ref name=girl-14>{{cite news|title=Girl (14) Wins Tokyo Trip|last=O'Keefe|first=Carolyn|work=[[The Herald-Sun]]|page=12|date=13 September 1964|location=Melbourne, Victoria}}</ref>  The event was the Australian qualifying competition for the 1964 Summer Paralympics.<ref name=Stinger/>

Around the time that Elizabeth was starting to prepare for the Paralympics, she was a student at [[St Hilda's Anglican School for Girls]], a member of the West Perth Swimming Club, and an avid surfer.  Edmondson put her surfing on hold to spend more time training.<ref name=girl-14/>

===Paralympics===
[[File:Xx0964---Elizabeth-Edmondson-in-pool---3a---photoshopped.jpg|thumb|Elizabeth Edmondson training at Beatty Park pool aged 14]]
[[File:Xx1164 - Ceeney and Edmondson handshake Tokyo Games - 3a - Scan.jpg|right|200px| Australian Paralympic Team members Daphne Ceeney (now Hilton) and Elizabeth Edmondson shake hands after Edmondson won gold and Ceeney silver in the 50m prone swimming event at the 1964 Tokyo Paralympic Games. They are pushed by Kevin Betts (Ceeney) and 'Johnno' Johnston (Edmondson)]]
[[File:Xx1164 - Australian athletes at athletics Tokyo Games - 3a - Scan.jpg|right|200px|Australian Paralympic Team members in the in-field at the athletics during the 1964 Tokyo Paralympic Games. From left (seated) Frank Ponta, team official John Johnston, Elizabeth Edmondson, unknown and Bill Mather-Brown]]
{{quote box
|align=right
|width=20%
|quote=Swimming allowed me to move through the water with a certain amount of grace and my disability seemed to disappear in the dimensions of the pool. It got me physically fit,  which was a big plus. I enjoyed the competition, the travel and most of all people I met became firm friends. Sport has meant a great deal to me.
|source=Elizabeth Edmondson<ref name=mather-brown>{{cite book|last=Mather-Brown|first=Bill|authorlink=Bill Mather-Brown|title=The fight in the dog|year=2002|publisher=T. Beck|location=Perth|isbn=0958000107|pages=273}}</ref> 
}}
At the age of 14 years and 4 months,<ref name=age>{{cite web|url=http://www.dsa.org.au/life_site/sport/case.html |accessdate=14 September 2011 |publisher=Disability Services Australia |title=A History of Athletes |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706124653/http://www.dsa.org.au/life_site/sport/case.html |archivedate= 6 July 2011 |df= }}</ref> Edmondson was an Australian [[Paralympic Games|Paralympic]] competitor.  She was the youngest competitor at the [[1964 Summer Paralympics]] in Tokyo among athletes from all nations.<ref name=young-heroine-school>{{cite news|title=Young Heroine Returns|work=[[The West Australian]]|page=7|date=19 November 1964|location=Perth, Western Australia}}</ref> She was the youngest Paralympic gold medallist for Australia for 48 years, until [[Maddison Elliott]] won a bronze medal at the [[2012 Summer Paralympics|2012 London Paralympics]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/sport/australias-paralympics-gold-win-tally-streaks-ahead-20120901-256mw.html|title=Australia's Paralympics gold win tally streaks ahead|publisher=[[The Age]]|date=1 September 2012|accessdate=5 September 2012}}</ref> She won three gold medals in the 1964 Summer Paralympics in the following events: the women's class 5 50 metre breaststroke with a world record time of 1.04.6;<ref name=Paralympic-results-536>{{cite book|page=536|title=Paralympic Games results : Rome 1960 to Atlanta 1996|author1=International Paralympic Committee|author2=Sydney Paralympic Organising Committee|location=Sydney, Australia|publisher=Sydney Paralympic Organising Committee|year=2000|oclc=223030936}}</ref> women's class 5 50 metre backstroke with a world record time of 0.50.8;<ref name=Paralympic-results-535>{{cite book|page=535|title=Paralympic Games results : Rome 1960 to Atlanta 1996|author1=International Paralympic Committee|author2=Sydney Paralympic Organising Committee|location=Sydney, Australia|publisher=Sydney Paralympic Organising Committee|year=2000|oclc=223030936}}</ref> women's class 5 complete 50 metre freestyle with a world record time of 0.39.7.<ref name=Paralympic-results-534>{{cite book|page=534|title=Paralympic Games results : Rome 1960 to Atlanta 1996|author1=International Paralympic Committee|author2=Sydney Paralympic Organising Committee|location=Sydney, Australia|publisher=Sydney Paralympic Organising Committee|year=2000|oclc=223030936}}</ref><ref name=Paralympic-results-512>{{cite book|page=512|title=Paralympic Games results : Rome 1960 to Atlanta 1996|author1=International Paralympic Committee|author2=Sydney Paralympic Organising Committee|location=Sydney, Australia|publisher=Sydney Paralympic Organising Committee|year=2000|oclc=223030936}}</ref> At the conclusion of the 1964 Games, Edmondson's parents acknowledged that swimming had greatly helped their daughter, but felt that she needed to quit the sport and concentrate on her education because swimming would not provide her with standing in life.<ref name=another-golden>{{cite news|title=Another Golden Girl, Elizabeth Beats Polio|publisher=[[Australian Associated Press|AAP]], [[Reuters]]|work=[[The Herald-Sun]]|page=15|date=11 November 1964|location=Melbourne, Victoria}}</ref> After the 1964 games, Edmondson returned home and prepared for school exams.<ref name=young-heroine-school/>

Edmondson and [[Lorraine Dodd]] met [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother]] at a garden party hosted at [[Government House, Perth|Government House]] when she visited Perth in 1966.<ref name=royal-interest>{{cite news|title=Royal Interest|work=[[The West Australian]]|page=1|date=30 March 1966|location=Perth, Western Australia}}</ref><ref name=paraplegic-training>{{cite news|title=Paraplegics in Training For Games|work=[[The West Australian]]|page=16|date=11 April 1966|location=Perth, Western Australia}}</ref> Edmondson did not compete in the [[1966 Commonwealth Paraplegic Games]],<ref name=Stinger/> due to difficulty finding funding to go to Jamaica, a plight common to many Western Australian athletes.<ref name=paraplegic-training/>

Edmondson won a gold medal at the [[1968 Summer Paralympics]] in Tel Aviv in the 50 metre freestyle class 4 incomplete swimming event with a world record time of 0.44.1 and a gold medal in the 100 metre open freestyle swim event with a world record time of 1.33.0. She also won a silver medal in Women's 50m Backstroke class 4 incomplete in a time of 52.3.<ref name=Paralympic-results-511>{{cite book|page=511|title=Paralympic Games results : Rome 1960 to Atlanta 1996|author1=International Paralympic Committee|author2=Sydney Paralympic Organising Committee|location=Sydney, Australia|publisher=Sydney Paralympic Organising Committee|year=2000|oclc=223030936}}</ref>

Edmondson competed with limited mobility in the water, during the Paralympics and the rest of her swimming career: She could only use her arms and shoulders to move through the water. Edmondson's swimming coach, Tony Howson, claimed that her swimming times were similar to those of able-bodied girls of the same age.<ref name=tweed>{{cite news|title=Sports Looking Glass|last=Donovan|first=Syd|work=The Daily News (Tweed)|page=8|date=19 November 1964|location=[[Tweed Heads, New South Wales]], Australia}}</ref> She stopped competing after the 1968 Games for financial reasons, and was employed at [[Telstra]].<ref name="Stinger"/>

===Masters swimming===
[[File:21 birthday Ruth.jpeg|thumb|left|Elizabeth Edmondson (seated) at her daughter's 21st birthday.]]
{{Quote box
|align=right
|width=20%
|quote= I was diagnosed with breast cancer and underwent a lumpectomy. After surgery, I wrote to my friends and told them I now had one concave and one convex breast. One friend then asked "Does that mean you will swim round in circles?" Luckily, when I resumed swimming in early 2009 I was still able to swim in a straight line!
|source=Elizabeth Edmondson<ref name=newsletter-8/>
}}
In 2006, she started to participate in competitive swimming again when she joined the Stadium Masters Swimming Club. In 2008, she qualified for the [[FINA World Masters Championships]] and swam a personal best time in the 800m Freestyle.<ref name=Stinger/> From 2007 to 2009, she competed in several swimming events in a variety of strokes and distances around Australia in the women's 55–59 age group.<ref name=masters-2011>{{cite web|url=http://www.portal.aussi.org.au/results/results.php?year=----&name=ELIZABETH+EDMONDSON&aussiid=&pb=no&sort=agegrp&Show=Show&js=on|accessdate=19 September 2011|title=Masters Swimming Australia – Results|publisher=MSA Portal|first=Frank|last=Braun}}</ref> In October 2007, at the 11th [[Australian Masters Games]], she won 7 individual gold medals and a  1 gold in a relay as a disabled swimmer. She also won a bronze medal in a member of a team in an abled bodied relay event.

In February 2009, she swam in the 12th [[Australian Masters Games]] and won 7 individual gold medals and 2 gold for relay events as a disabled swimmer .<ref name=masters-games>{{cite web|url=http://australianmastersgames.com.au/_uploads/res/1_60.pdf|title=12th Australian Masters Games  Swimming Results|accessdate=19 September 2011|year=2009|publisher=Australian Masters Games}}</ref>

At the [[2009 World Masters Games]] in [[Sydney]], she won four gold medals and a silver medal in the age group 55 to 69 years.<ref>{{cite web|title=Swimming Events|url=http://www.foxsportspulse.com/assoc_page.cgi?c=17-7745-0-0-0&sID=159886|work=World Masrers Games website|accessdate=8 March 2014}}</ref>

Edmondson competed at the 2010 Australian National Masters Swimming Championships, held in [[Launceston, Tasmania]]. She competed in twelve individual events, and set eleven individual personal records.  Her travel to the event was paid for by Wheelchair Sports WA through the Sir [[George Bedbrook]] Scholarship fund.<ref name=launceston>{{cite web|url=http://www.wheelchairsportswa.org.au/news100430G.htm|accessdate=19 September 2011|date=30 April 2010|publisher=Wheelchair Sports WA|title=Elizabeth Mills at Launceston Swimming Championships}}</ref>

Edmondson competed at the 2011 X111 Australian Masters Games held in [[Adelaide, South Australia]]. She competed as a disabled swimmer in six individual events and four relays and won ten gold medals.<ref name=masters-games2>{{cite web |url=http://australianmastersgames.com.au/Extra.asp?id=225|title=Australian Masters Games Results: Swimming|accessdate=21 October 2011}}</ref><ref name=snappets-green>{{cite news|journal=Snappets Newsletter|publisher=Stadium Snappers Masters Swimming Club Inc|url=https://assets.clubsonline.com.au/assets/console/document/documents/SNAPPETS%20October%202011.pdf|date=October 2011|page=1|title=PRESIDENT’S REPORT|first=Barry|last=Green|location=Western Australia, Australia|format=PDF}}</ref> Edmondson competed at the 2013 X1V Australian Masters Games held in Geelong, Victoria. She competed as a disabled swimmer in seven individual events and two  relays and won nine  gold medals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://14amgregistration.fusesport.com/extra.asp?ID=861|title=Swimming Results and Schedules|publisher=Australian Masters Games|accessdate=7 October 2013}}</ref>

Edmondson swam in the British Long Distance Swimming Association's One Hour Postal Swim from 2009 to 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=Results|url=http://postalswim.com/results.html|work=Postal Swimming|accessdate=13 March 2014}}</ref> She is also a qualified swimming marshall.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Masters swimming WA awards presentation|journal=Snappets|date=June 2010|url=http://assets.imgstg.com/assets/console/document/documents/SNAPPETS_June_2008.pdf|accessdate=13 March 2014|format=PDF}}</ref>

==Recognition==
Edmondson was awarded the [[Australian Sports Medal]] in 2000, in recognition of her work as a  swimmer.<ref name=newsletter-8>{{cite journal|url=http://www.hconc.org.au/publications/01%20Health%20Matters/Health%20Matters%20%20Issue%2081%20Pages%201-30.pdf|accessdate=19 September 2011|page=8|journal=Your Voice on Health|publisher=The Health Consumers‘ Council WA|issue=81|date=July–September 2010|title=The Jelly Bean Walk — My Story|last=Edmondson|first=Elizabeth|format=PDF}}</ref> Edmondson was inducted into the Swimming Western Australia Hall of Fame in 2008.<ref name=break-rcords>{{cite web|url=http://www.mswa.asn.au/newsletter/DS-Spring2008oct.pdf|date=Spring 2008|accessdate=19 September 2011|title=Stadium Snappers|first=Richard|last=Diggins |publisher=Masters Swimming Australia|page=6|format=PDF}}</ref> In 2009, Edmondson was inducted into the Wheelchair Sports WA Hall of Fame.<ref name=wahof>{{cite web|url=http://www.wheelchairsportswa.org.au/asa.htm|year=2010|title=Awards Night|publisher=Wheelchair Sports WA|accessdate=19 September 2011}}</ref> Edmondson was awarded a Certificate of Commendation in 2012 by Masters Swimming Western Australia  for her services to Masters Swimming.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://assets.imgstg.com/assets/console/document/documents/Snappers%20June%202012.pdf|title=Commendation|work=Snappers Newsletter|page=2|date=June 2012|format=PDF|accessdate=6 August 2012}}</ref>

In 2018 she became the first inductee into the Swimming WA Hall of Legends<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wa.swimming.org.au/visageimages/Hall%20of%20Legends%20-%20Edmondson.pdf|title=Swimming WA Hall of Legends Induction|last=|first=|date=26 May 2018|website=Swimming WA|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180527013022/https://wa.swimming.org.au/visageimages/Hall%20of%20Legends%20-%20Edmondson.pdf|archive-date=27 May 2018|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> recognising "outstanding swimming performances at an international level... deemed to have inspired the nation and to have established the name of the athlete, their State and their country on the world stage."<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wa.swimming.org.au/page.php?id=407|title=Hall of Legends|last=|first=|date=|website=Swimming WA|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180527013207/https://wa.swimming.org.au/page.php?id=407|archive-date=27 May 2018|dead-url=|access-date=2018-05-27}}</ref>

==Personal life==

After she started working for Telstra, she married Ken Mills and had a daughter, Ruth.<ref name=Stinger/> In December 2008, Edmondson was diagnosed with [[breast cancer]]. Her treatment involved having a [[lumpectomy]].<ref name=newsletter-8/>

